<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Mackenzie, Roderick. An Account of the Athabasca Indians by a Partner of the North West Company, 1795. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0032</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">24</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">When a Greenlander dies, the relations throw all the Utensils, furniture, and clothes, out of the house, as impure and unpropitious.  They lament the loss of the deceased with tears and hideous howling; and bury him under a heap of stones, dressed in his best apparel with his legs bent under him.  Near the place of interment they deposit the Utensils or implements belonging to the deceased of either sex, lest the sight of them should recal the remembrance of their departed friend, and renew their grief and affliction.  Their songs are satyrical ballads, sung extempore at their assemblies, and accompanied by a kind of drum beaten with the fingers, who also entertain the company with strange gesticulations.  The Greenlanders pass a corpse through the window, or the back part of a house: and they place a Dog's head near the grave of a child to guide his soul in the right path.</p>

